<P>
U.S. Employment Outlook Dims: Fewer U.S. companies plan to increase hiring in 
the final quarter of 1989 than the previous year, largely because of softness 
in the Northeast, a survey of U.S. firms has found. The survey, conducted by 
temporary employment agency Manpower Inc., found that 26% of nearly 14,000 
employers questioned by telephone planned to increase hiring from October 
through December, down from 28% in 1988. Companies in the Northeast had the 
least ambitious hiring plans, with 22% saying they would add to their staff, a 
seven-year low, compared to 27% last year. 
