<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: CERRITOS ADDED TO QUARANTINE AREAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A ban on the export of home-grown fruit and vegetables was placed on the 
Cerritos area Wednesday because of an infestation of Oriental fruit flies. 
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's ban means a total of 190 square miles in Los Angeles County are 
under quarantine for agricultural pests. 
</P>
<P>
Additionally, three Oriental fruit flies were detected in Burbank, prompting 
officials to order ground spraying of insecticide on fence posts, trees and 
utility poles. 
</P>
<P>
Oriental fruit flies are potentially as destructive as the more notorious 
Mediterranean fruit flies, which agricultural officials are battling over 70 
square miles north of downtown Los Angeles. But Oriental fruit flies have 
become a more common occurrence in Southern California, and eradication efforts 
have not involved the controversial aerial spraying of malathion. 
</P>
<P>
The latest quarantine was imposed on a 79-square-mile area straddling the Los 
Angeles-Orange County line. Under the quarantine, commercially grown fruit and 
vegetables must be treated and approved by the county agricultural commissioner 
before it can be removed from the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Column 
</P>
