<HEADLINE>
<P>
LLOYD'S OF LONDON REPORTS REBOUNDING PROFITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Lloyd's of London insurance market, which reports results three years in 
arrears because of long delays in settling claims, said today that profits 
rebounded strongly in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
It put pretax profit for the year at $1 billion at current exchange rates, more 
than three times its profits of $303 million in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
The latest figures show underwriting profit of $1.15 billion and total net 
premium income of $5.75 billion. 
</P>
<P>
Lloyd's Chairman Murray Lawrence said that although prospects for 1987 were 
encouraging, results for the next three years would be less spectacular, with 
marine and aviation markets in particular unlikely to produce satisfactory 
profits in 1988 and 1989. 
</P>
<P>
"There are signs that some important areas of the market are approaching the 
bottom of the trough, and I believe that during 1990, rates in these areas 
should begin to harden and move upward to more realistic levels," he said. 
</P>
<P>
The marine market had an underwriting return of 19.7% before currency gains, 
but excessive capacity and worsening claims were producing unfavorable 
conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
