<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
U.S. WARNS S. KOREA ON TRADE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SEOUL 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The United States has given South Korea five months to resolve 
telecommunications disputes or risk trade sanctions, Seoul officials said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
They also said little progress was being made in the first round of U.S.-South 
Korean talks on opening Seoul's market to American telecommunication goods and 
services. 
</P>
<P>
U.S. delegates, led by the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative's director 
for Korean affairs, Gordana Earp, said South Korea must show sincere commitment 
in opening its market by Feb. 18, 1990, or incur stiff penalties under new U.S. 
trade laws. 
</P>
<P>
Washington accused Seoul in February of keeping its markets closed to American 
telecom products. It said it would slap up to 100% tariffs on 
telecommunications imports from South Korea if bilateral talks fell through. 
</P>
</TEXT>
